b'<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\n\n\n<!DOCTYPE workbook_page PUBLIC " -//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Workbook Page MathML 3.8//EN" "http://oli.web.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_workbook_page_mathml_3_8.dtd">\n<workbook_page id="p3_molarity" xmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/"\n    xmlns:bib="http://bibtexml.sf.net/" xmlns:pref="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/preferences/"\n    xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:theme="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/presentation/"\n    xmlns:wb="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/activity/workbook/">\n\n\n    <head>\n        <title>Molarity</title>\n        <objref idref="molarity"/>\n\n    </head>\n\n    <body>\n\n        <section id="p3_molarity_DE1">\n           <title></title>\n           <body> <p>Concentrations of solutions may be quantitatively assessed using a wide variety of\n            measurement units, each convenient for particular applications. <extra><anchor>Molarity (M)</anchor><meaning><material><p>unit of concentration, defined as the number of moles of solute dissolved in 1 liter of solution</p></material></meaning></extra> is a useful\n            concentration unit for many applications in chemistry. Molarity is defined as the number\n            of moles of solute in exactly 1 liter (1 L) of the solution.</p>\n\n        <image src="../../../webcontent/green_line.png"></image>\n        \n        <dl>\n            <dt><em>Molarity Equation</em></dt>\n            <dd><formula>$$\\mathrm{Molarity}\\;=\\;\\frac{\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm{solute}}{\\mathrm\n                    L\\;\\mathrm{solution}}$$</formula></dd>\n        </dl>\n       <image src="../../../webcontent/green_line.png"></image></body></section>\n       \n        <example id="p3_molarity_EX1">\n            <p>A 355\xe2\x88\x92mL soft drink sample contains 0.133 mol of sucrose (table sugar). What is the\n                molar concentration of sucrose in the beverage?</p>\n\n            <p>Since the molar amount of solute and the volume of solution are both given, the\n                molarity can be calculated using the definition of molarity. Per this definition,\n                the solution volume must be converted from mL to L:</p>\n\n            <formula>$$355\\;\\mathrm{mL}\\;\\times\\frac{1\\;\\mathrm L}{1000\\;\\mathrm{mL}}\\;=\\;0.355\\;\\mathrm L$$</formula>\n            <formula>$$M\\;=\\;\\frac{\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm{solute}}{\\mathrm L\\;\\mathrm{solution}}\\;=\\;\\frac{0.133\\;\\mathrm{mol}}{0.355\\;\\mathrm L}\\;=\\;0.375\\;\\mathrm M$$</formula>\n        </example>\n\n\n        <example id="p3_molarity_EX2">\n            <p>How much sugar (mol) is contained in 10 mL of the soda described in the example\n                above?</p>\n\n            <p>In this case, we can rearrange the definition of molarity to isolate the quantity\n                sought, moles of sugar. We then substitute the value for molarity that we derived in\n                the previous example, 0.375 M.</p>\n\n            <formula>$$\\begin{array}{l}\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm M\\;=\\;\\frac{\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm{solute}}{\\mathrm L\\;\\mathrm{solution}}\\\\\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm{solute}\\;=\\;\\mathrm M\\;\\times\\;\\mathrm L\\;\\mathrm{solution}\\end{array}$$</formula>\n\n            <formula>$$\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm{solute}\\;=0.375\\;\\mathrm M\\;\\times\\;(10\\;\\mathrm{mL}\\;\\times\\;\\frac{1\\;\\mathrm L}{1000\\;\\mathrm{mL}})\\;=\\;0.004\\;\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm{sugar}$$</formula>\n\n        </example>\n\n        <wb:inline idref="molarity_lbd_1" purpose="learnbydoing"/>\n\n        <example id="p3_molarity_EX3">\n            <p>Distilled white vinegar is a solution of acetic acid, CH<sub>3</sub>CO<sub>2</sub>H,\n                in water. A 0.500\xe2\x88\x92L vinegar solution contains 25.2 g of acetic acid. What is the\n                concentration of the acetic acid solution in units of molarity?</p>\n\n            <p>To calculate the molarity, you need mol of solute. Convert grams of acetic acid to\n                mol.</p>\n\n            <formula>$$\\require{cancel}25.2\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm g\\;{\\mathrm{CH}}_3{\\mathrm{CO}}_2\\mathrm H}\\;\\times\\frac{1\\;\\mathrm{mol}\\;{\\mathrm{CH}}_3{\\mathrm{CO}}_2\\mathrm H}{60.06\\cancel{\\;\\mathrm g\\;{\\mathrm{CH}}_3{\\mathrm{CO}}_2\\mathrm H}}\\;=\\;0.4196\\;\\mathrm{mol}\\;{\\mathrm{CH}}_3{\\mathrm{CO}}_2\\mathrm H$$</formula>\n\n            <p>Substitute the values for mol and L into the definition of molarity.</p>\n\n            <formula>$$\\frac{0.4196\\;\\mathrm{mol}}{0.500\\;\\mathrm L}\\;=\\;0.839\\;\\mathrm M$$</formula>\n        </example>\n\n        <example id="p3_molarity_EX4">\n\n            <p>How many grams of NaCl are contained in 0.250 L of a 5.30\xe2\x88\x92M solution?</p>\n\n            <p>The volume and molarity of the solution are specified. We can rearrange the\n                definition of molarity to isolate mole. </p>\n\n            <p>mol solute = M \xc3\x97 L solution</p>\n\n            <formula>$$\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm{solute}\\;=\\;5.30\\;\\frac{\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm{NaCl}}{1\\;\\mathrm L}\\;\\times\\;0.250\\;\\mathrm L\\;=\\;1.325\\;\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm{NaCl}$$</formula>\n\n            <p>Finally, this molar amount is used to derive the mass of NaCl:</p>\n\n            <formula>$$1.325\\;\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm{NaCl}\\;\\times\\;\\frac{58.44\\;\\mathrm g\\;\\mathrm{NaCl}}{1\\;\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm{NaCl}}\\;=\\;77.4\\;\\mathrm g\\;\\mathrm{NaCl}$$</formula>\n        </example>\n\n        <section id="p3_molarity_DE2">\n          <title></title>\n          <body>  <p>When performing calculations stepwise, it is important to refrain from rounding any\n            intermediate calculation results, which can lead to rounding errors in the final result.\n            In the previous example, the molar amount of NaCl computed in the first step, 1.325 mol,\n            would be properly rounded to 1.32 mol if it were to be reported; however, although the\n            last digit (5) is not significant, it must be retained as a guard digit in the\n            intermediate calculation. If we had not retained this guard digit, the final calculation\n            for the mass of NaCl would have been 77.1 g, a difference of 0.3 g.</p>\n\n        <p>In addition to retaining a guard digit for intermediate calculations, we can also avoid\n            rounding errors by performing computations in a single step. This eliminates\n            intermediate steps so that only the final result is rounded.</p>\n</body></section>\n        <wb:inline idref="molarity_lbd_2" purpose="learnbydoing"/>\n\n        <wb:inline idref="molarity_digt_1" purpose="didigetthis"/>\n\n     \n        <section id="p3_molarity_DE3">\n            <title>Concentration of Ions</title>\n            <body>\n\n                <p>In many situations you will be concerned with the molarity of a solution as\n                    described above. However, sometimes it may be useful to consider the\n                    concentration of individual ions in solution. Remember the equation for\n                    molarity:</p>\n                <formula>$$\\require{cancel}\\mathrm{Molarity}\\;=\\;\\frac{\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm{solute}}{\\mathrm L\\;\\mathrm{solution}}$$</formula>\n\n              \n\n                <p>When ionic compounds are dissolved in water they dissociate into their\n                    constituent ions. When sodium chloride, NaCl, is dissolved in water it produces one\n                        Na<sup>+</sup> and one Cl<sup>\xe2\x88\x92</sup> ion per formula unit dissolved.\n                    However, when calcium chloride, CaCl<sub>2</sub>, is dissolved in water it produces one\n                        Ca<sup>2</sup><sup>+</sup> and two Cl<sup>\xe2\x88\x92</sup> ions per formula unit\n                    dissolved. This means that the concentration of Cl<sup>\xe2\x88\x92</sup> ions will be\n                    twice the concentration of Ca<sup>2</sup><sup>+</sup> ions when CaCl<sub>2</sub> is\n                    dissolved in water. Likewise the concentration of Cl<sup>\xe2\x88\x92</sup> ions will be\n                    twice the concentration of the solution.</p>\n\n              <materials>\n                  <material>\n                      <image src="../webcontent/nacl_ions.gif" width="350" alt="When NaCl is dissolved in water, the Na+ and Cl- ions separate."></image>\n                  </material>\n                  <material>\n                      <image src="../webcontent/cacl2_ions.gif" width="350" alt="When CaCl2 is dissolved in water, the Ca2+ and Cl- ions separate. There are 2 Cl- ions for every one Ca2+ ion."></image>\n                  </material>\n              </materials>\n                \n                <p>Animations developed from PhET Interactive Simulations, University of Colorado\n                    Boulder, <link href="https://phet.colorado.edu">https://phet.colorado.edu</link>. </p>\n\n                <p>The solution of CaCl<sub>2</sub> in the right animation has twice the\n                    concentration of Cl<sup>\xe2\x88\x92</sup> to Ca<sup>2</sup><sup>+</sup>. </p>\n            </body>\n        </section>\n\n        <example id="p3_molarity_EX5">\n            <p>What is the concentration in molarity of a CaCl<sub>2</sub> solution in which 4.85 g\n                of CaCl<sub>2</sub> has been dissolved in water to form 850 mL of solution? What is\n                the concentration in molarity of the Ca<sup>2</sup><sup>+</sup> ions in the solution\n                and the Cl<sup>\xe2\x88\x92</sup> ions in the solution?</p>\n\n            <p>Calculating the molarity of the CaCl<sub>2</sub> solution is the same process as we\n                have seen previously.</p>\n\n            <formula>$$\\begin{array}{l}4.85\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm g\\;{\\mathrm{CaCl}}_2}\\;\\times\\;\\frac{1\\;\\mathrm{mol}\\;{\\mathrm{CaCl}}_2}{110.95\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm g\\;{\\mathrm{CaCl}}_2}}\\;=\\;0.0437\\;\\mathrm{mol}\\;{\\mathrm{CaCl}}_2\\\\\\\\\\mathrm M\\;=\\;\\frac{0.0437\\;\\mathrm{mol}}{0.850\\;\\mathrm L}\\;=\\;0.0514\\;\\mathrm M\\end{array}$$</formula>\n\n            <p>The concentration of the solution is 0.0514 M.</p>\n\n            <p>Since there is one Ca<sup>2</sup><sup>+</sup> ion produced per formula unit of\n                    CaCl<sub>2</sub>, the concentration of Ca<sup>2</sup><sup>+</sup> is also 0.0514\n                M.</p>\n\n            <p>Since there are two Cl<sup>\xe2\x88\x92</sup> ions produced per formula unit of\n                CaCl<sub>2</sub>, the concentration of Cl<sup>\xe2\x88\x92</sup> is:</p>\n\n            <formula>$$2\\;\\times\\;0.0514\\;\\mathrm M\\;=\\;0.103\\;\\mathrm M$$</formula>\n\n            <p>The concentration of the solution is 0.0514 M.</p>\n\n            <p> The concentration of the Ca<sup>2</sup><sup>+</sup> is 0.0514 M.</p>\n\n            <p>The concentration of the Cl<sup>\xe2\x88\x92</sup> is 0.103 M.</p>\n        </example>\n\n        <wb:inline idref="molarity_lbd_3" purpose="learnbydoing"/>\n\n        <wb:inline idref="molarity_digt_2" purpose="didigetthis"/>\n\n        <p>Adapted from <link href="https://cnx.org/contents/havxkyvS@9.422:b39avmGq@29/Preface"\n                >Openstax Chemistry</link> under <link\n                href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/"> Creative Commons Attribution\n                4.0 License. </link></p>\n        <p>Download for free at <link\n                href="http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312"\n                >http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312.</link></p>\n\n    </body>\n\n</workbook_page>\n'